%U A396223 6346,4753,6462,10195,7801,8614,8203,7555,14723,7421,8031,19886,8442,15275,9211,12486
%N A396223 a(n) is the largest integer area attainable by a polygon with side lengths divisors(A005101(n)).
%C A396223 For nonabundant numbers there is no positive-area polygon: the longest side is not less than the sum of the others.
%C A396223 The maximal area A_max is attained by a cyclic polygon when such a cyclic polygon with the given side lengths exists. If no cyclic polygon exists, the area supremum A_sup equals the semicyclic limit as the radius approaches one half of the longest side from above (so the longest side tends to a diameter).
%C A396223 By continuity of area with fixed side lengths, attainable areas form an interval: [0, A_max] in the cyclic case, [0, A_sup) otherwise. Hence the largest integer area equals floor(A_max) (cyclic case) or floor(A_sup) (semicyclic case), and it is attained by some polygon.
%C A396223 The sequence is not monotone. Sometimes the longest side fixes the best circumradius at half of the largest divisor (diameter case); other times the circle must be larger. Moving between these explains the dips.
%H A396223 Felix Huber, <a href="/A396223/a396223.pdf">Illustration of a(1) and a(12)</a>
